to many simultaneous needs, including those imposed by the distribution of resources and enemies around the nest, Professors Oster and Wilson are able to construct a series of mathematical models to characterize the agents of natural selection that promote particular caste systems.The social insects play a key role in the subject of sociobiology because their social organization is so rigid and can be related to genetic evolution. Because of this important consideration, the authors' work has consequences not only for entomology but also for general evolutionary theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aAllometric space.  aAllometry.  aAuslander, D.  aBrian.  aBrown.  aCamponotus (carpenter ants).  aCaste distribution function (CDF).  aDemography.  aEaton (army ants).  aEnergy as utility.  aFormica (ants).  aGuckenheimer, J.  aHare, Hope.  aIndividual-level selection.  aJanzen, D. H.  aMichener, C. D.  aMirmirani, M.  aMonomorium (ants).  aMyrmica (ants).  aNash equilibrium.  aOecophylla (weaver ants), frontispiece.  aOster, G. F.  aPheidole (ants).  aPogonomyrmex (harvesting ants).  aPolistes (paper wasps).  aResource distribution function (RDF).  aSchmidt, G. H.  aSoldier caste.  aTemporal castes.  aTrivers, R. L.  aWilson, E. O.1 aWilson, Edward O., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209326.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMAL